2. Overall Description
2.1 Major Functions of Existing System
Manual Record-Keeping: Farmers maintain physical notebooks for tracking planting dates, input usage, and harvest yields with no standardized format across regions.
Agricultural Extension Services: Government extension workers provide periodic visits to farming communities, reaching only 30% of farmers with often generic information.
Market Information Systems: Radio broadcasts and physical market boards provide price information, supplemented by word-of-mouth sharing among farmers and traders.
Weather Information: National Meteorological Agency provides forecasts through radio and television, with limited localized and real-time information.
Disease and Pest Management: Visual inspection by farmers or extension workers, traditional remedies, chemical recommendations from input suppliers (often biased).
Crop Selection and Planning: Decisions based on traditional knowledge and previous experiences with limited consideration of soil conditions or market demand.
Knowledge Transfer: Oral transmission from elders, farmer field schools organized by NGOs, limited documentation of indigenous practices.
Financial Management: Cash-based transactions with limited record-keeping, informal credit systems, limited access to formal banking and insurance.

2.2 Users of Current System
Primary Users:
1.	Smallholder Farmers: 15 million with average 1-2 hectare holdings, mixed technology access
2.	Agricultural Extension Workers: Government employees with high farmer-to-worker ratio (1:5000)
3.	Input Suppliers and Agro-dealers: Primary source of technical advice with commercial bias
4.	Market Traders and Middlemen: Key source of market price information with potential exploitation
5.	Agricultural Researchers: Limited field testing and feedback mechanisms
6.	Government Officials: Limited real-time data on agricultural conditions
7.	NGOs and Development Organizations: Project-based interventions with sustainability concerns
8.	Financial Institutions: Limited data for risk assessment in rural areas
User Characteristics:
●	Digital Literacy: High (15%), Medium (35%), Low (50%)
●	Language Preferences: Amharic (29%), Afaan Oromo (34%), Other (37%), English (limited)
●	Technology Access: Smartphone (40%), Feature phone (85%), Internet (25%), Digital payments (15%)
●	Gender Considerations: Women = 40-50% of labor force but 30% less extension access, 40% less credit access
2.3 Drawbacks of the Current System
Information-Related Drawbacks:
1.	Information Asymmetry: Farmers have limited market information, input suppliers have product advantage
2.	Information Delay: Weather forecasts received too late, disease outbreaks identified after damage
3.	Information Inaccuracy: Traditional weather prediction unreliable, visual disease diagnosis error-prone
4.	Information Fragmentation: Conflicting advice from different sources, no integrated platform
Operational Drawbacks:
1.	Low Productivity: Cereal yields 1-2 vs potential 4-5 tons/hectare, post-harvest losses 20-30%
2.	High Transaction Costs: Significant travel time, multiple intermediaries reduce profits
3.	Limited Scalability: Extension services can't reach all farmers, successful practices not easily replicated
4.	Sustainability Concerns: Soil degradation, climate vulnerability, youth disinterest
Specific Pain Points:
●	Farmers: "I don't know which crop will give best return," "By the time I see disease, it's too late"
●	Extension Workers: "I can't visit all farmers regularly," "Farmers don't always follow recommendations"
●	Policy Makers: "No real-time field data," "Hard to measure program impact"
●	Researchers: "Research findings don't always reach farmers," "Limited feedback for improvement"
2.4 Business Rules of the Proposed System
User Management Rules:
1.	All users must register with valid phone/email and OTP verification
2.	Unique user ID generated for each farmer
3.	Role-based access control (Farmer, Extension Worker, Admin, Expert)
4.	Farmers can only access/modify their own data
Data Management Rules:
1.	Location data collected with user consent
2.	Image data must meet minimum quality standards
3.	Personal data encrypted at rest and in transit
4.	Farmers control what data is shared and with whom
Agricultural Decision Rules:
1.	Recommendations based on multi-factor analysis with minimum 70% confidence threshold
2.	Disease detection requires minimum image quality, expert validation below 80% confidence
3.	Planting dates calculated based on location-specific weather patterns
4.	Yield predictions include confidence intervals and risk factors
Operational Rules:
1.	Weather alerts for extreme conditions, disease alerts based on regional outbreaks
2.	All community posts moderated for appropriateness and accuracy
3.	Basic features free, premium features require subscription with trial periods
4.	Regular updates deployed during low-usage periods with advance notification
Compliance Rules:
1.	System compliant with Ethiopian data protection regulations
2.	Recommendations comply with Ministry of Agriculture guidelines
3.	Pesticide recommendations follow integrated pest management principles
4.	Regular compliance audits conducted
3. Proposed System
3.1 Overview of the System
Smart Gebere is a comprehensive digital agriculture platform designed to transform how Ethiopian farmers access information, make decisions, and manage their farms. The system leverages artificial intelligence, real-time data, and mobile technology to bridge the gap between traditional farming knowledge and modern agricultural science.
System Architecture:
The platform follows a modular microservices architecture with five layers:
1.	Presentation Layer: Mobile app (Android/iOS), responsive web interface, voice interface
2.	Application Layer: AI recommendation engine, image processing, planning algorithms
3.	Data Layer: User data management, agricultural knowledge base, real-time data integration
4.	Integration Layer: External APIs (weather, market), partner systems, government systems
5.	Administration Layer: User management, content management, system monitoring
Core Components:
●	Farmer Dashboard: Central hub with personalized information and quick actions
●	Crop Recommendation Engine: AI-powered suggestions based on multi-factor analysis
●	Disease Detection System: Image-based identification and treatment recommendations
●	Farm Planning Module: Week-by-week activity schedules and progress tracking
●	Yield Prediction System: AI-powered estimation with risk assessment
●	Field Mapping Tool: GPS-based boundary mapping and management
●	Market Intelligence Platform: Real-time prices, trends, and market access
●	Weather Advisory System: Current conditions, forecasts, and farming recommendations
●	Knowledge Base: Comprehensive agricultural information and learning materials
●	Community Platform: Farmer forums, expert Q&A, success sharing
●	Farm Records System: Digital record-keeping for all farm activities
Value Proposition:
●	For Farmers: Increased yields, reduced losses, better prices, time savings
●	For Extension Services: Extended reach, better targeting, real-time monitoring
●	For Government: Better policy implementation, real-time data, efficient resource allocation
●	For Researchers: Large-scale data collection, rapid technology testing
●	For Private Sector: Targeted opportunities, efficient supply chain, customer engagement
3.2 Functional Requirements
User Management Requirements:
FR-UM-001: System shall allow registration via phone/email with OTP verification
FR-UM-002: Support biometric authentication and secure session management
FR-UM-003: Allow multiple farm profiles per user with family member sub-users
FR-UM-004: Implement role-based access control with appropriate permissions
Crop Recommendation Requirements:
FR-CR-001: Collect GPS coordinates and analyze location-specific climate data
FR-CR-002: Multi-factor analysis considering soil, climate, market, and resources
FR-CR-003: Provide personalized recommendations with confidence scores and explanations
FR-CR-004: Support comparative analysis and "what-if" scenario evaluation
Disease Detection Requirements:
FR-DD-001: Allow image capture/upload with quality validation
FR-DD-002: Identify diseases using computer vision with confidence scores
FR-DD-003: Provide treatment options prioritized by effectiveness and safety
FR-DD-004: Support expert consultation requests with image/text communication
Farm Planning Requirements:
FR-FP-001: Generate week-by-week activity plans adjusted for actual planting dates
FR-FP-002: Calculate input requirements based on farm size and crop type
FR-FP-003: Track completion rates and identify schedule deviations
FR-FP-004: Send activity reminders and weather-based adjustment notifications
Yield Prediction Requirements:
FR-YP-001: Collect crop, soil, and management data for analysis
FR-YP-002: Generate predictions with confidence intervals and multiple scenarios
FR-YP-003: Identify yield-limiting factors and assess climate-related risks
FR-YP-004: Compare management scenarios and estimate return on investment
Field Mapping Requirements:
FR-FM-001: Support GPS-based boundary mapping with area calculation
FR-FM-002: Allow soil type recording and cropping history tracking
FR-FM-003: Track yield history and profitability by field
FR-FM-004: Integrate field data with crop recommendations and yield predictions
Market Intelligence Requirements:
FR-MI-001: Provide real-time prices with trends and historical data
FR-MI-002: Connect farmers with buyers and provide market location information
FR-MI-003: Analyze demand patterns and identify market opportunities
FR-MI-004: Integrate with mobile money services and financial products
Weather Advisory Requirements:
FR-WA-001: Integrate real-time weather data from multiple reliable sources
FR-WA-002: Provide weather-based farming recommendations and timing suggestions
FR-WA-003: Send extreme weather alerts and preparedness advice
FR-WA-004: Suggest climate-smart practices and adaptation strategies
Knowledge Base Requirements:
FR-KB-001: Provide comprehensive agricultural information organized by categories
FR-KB-002: Include interactive learning modules with progress tracking
FR-KB-003: Allow user knowledge contributions with validation
FR-KB-004: Provide access to agricultural experts through Q&A forums
Administrative Requirements:
FR-AD-001: Provide admin interface for user management and analytics
FR-AD-002: Support content management with versioning and scheduling
FR-AD-003: Provide system monitoring with performance tracking
FR-AD-004: Support ticket management and user feedback collection
3.3 Non-Functional Requirements
Performance Requirements:
NFR-PER-001: Load dashboard within 3 seconds on 3G, image processing within 10 seconds
NFR-PER-002: Support 100,000 concurrent users, process 10,000 images/hour
NFR-PER-003: App size <30MB Android/<50MB iOS, memory <200MB, battery <5%/hour
NFR-PER-004: Scale horizontally, support auto-scaling based on demand
Reliability Requirements:
NFR-REL-001: 99.5% uptime during farming seasons, max 4 hours monthly maintenance
NFR-REL-002: Continue operating during partial failures, automatic recovery from errors
NFR-REL-003: Ensure data consistency, prevent corruption, regular integrity checks
NFR-REL-004: Disaster recovery RTO 4 hours, daily backups with 30-day retention
Security Requirements:
NFR-SEC-001: Require authentication for all access, support multi-factor authentication
NFR-SEC-002: Encrypt personal data at rest and in transit, mask sensitive data
NFR-SEC-003: Use TLS 1.2+, protect against common attacks, implement rate limiting
NFR-SEC-004: Protect against OWASP Top 10 vulnerabilities, regular security scanning
Usability Requirements:
NFR-USA-001: Intuitive interface, consistent design, multiple language support
NFR-USA-002: First-time users perform basic tasks without training, in-app tutorials
NFR-USA-003: Minimal steps for common tasks, remember user preferences
NFR-USA-004: User satisfaction score >70, NPS >50, regular feedback collection
Compatibility Requirements:
NFR-COM-001: Support Android 7.0+, iOS 12.0+, recent browsers, responsive design
NFR-COM-002: Work on devices with minimum 2GB RAM, various screen sizes
NFR-COM-003: Integrate with common payment gateways, follow RESTful API principles
NFR-COM-004: Support data import/export, maintain backward compatibility
Maintainability Requirements:
NFR-MNT-001: Follow coding standards, 80% test coverage, manage technical debt
NFR-MNT-002: Modular architecture, clear interfaces, minimal dependencies
NFR-MNT-003: Configurable without code changes, feature flag control
NFR-MNT-004: Comprehensive logging, monitoring, debugging tools
Legal and Compliance Requirements:
NFR-LEG-001: Comply with Ethiopian data protection and agricultural regulations
NFR-LEG-002: Protect user privacy, ensure fair AI recommendations, respect indigenous knowledge
NFR-LEG-003: Comply with WCAG 2.1 Level AA accessibility standards
NFR-LEG-004: Support multiple languages, culturally appropriate content
3.4 Domain and Inverse Requirements
Agricultural Domain Requirements:
DR-AGR-001: Recommendations based on scientifically validated crop requirements
DR-AGR-002: Soil classification following standard taxonomy, fertility based on tests
DR-AGR-003: Consider current and projected climate conditions in recommendations
DR-AGR-004: Include market demand and prices in crop selection advice
DR-AGR-005: Promote sustainable practices following IPM principles
Ethiopian Context Requirements:
DR-ETH-001: Include indigenous crop varieties and traditional cultivation practices
DR-ETH-002: Tailor recommendations to different agro-ecological zones
DR-ETH-003: Align with Ministry of Agriculture guidelines and government programs
DR-ETH-004: Work with existing telecommunications and infrastructure limitations
User Context Requirements:
DR-USR-001: Design for varying digital literacy, multiple interaction modes
DR-USR-002: Content in local languages, simplified concepts, visual aids
DR-USR-003: Accessible and useful for women farmers, address gender-specific challenges
DR-USR-004: Basic features free, premium features affordable, clear value demonstration
Inverse Requirements (What the System Must NOT Do):
IR-AGR-001: Not recommend harmful practices or exceed safe pesticide rates
IR-AGR-002: Not provide recommendations with insufficient data or certainty
IR-AGR-003: Not recommend unsafe practices without proper precautions
IR-AGR-004: Not promote child labor or unethical practices
IR-TEC-001: Not claim 100% accuracy, clearly communicate AI limitations
IR-TEC-002: Not share user data without consent or retain unnecessarily
IR-TEC-003: Not be unavailable during critical periods or lose data
IR-TEC-004: Not require advanced technical skills or hide essential functions
IR-BUS-001: Not create dependency on specific products or bias toward advertisers
IR-BUS-002: Not violate laws or regulations or use deceptive terms
IR-BUS-003: Not use unsustainable business models or exploitative partnerships
IR-BUS-004: Not exacerbate inequalities or limit access to privileged groups
3.5 Design and Implementation Requirements
Architectural Requirements:
AR-001: Three-tier architecture (Presentation, Application, Data) with clear separation
AR-002: Microservices architecture with RESTful API communication
AR-003: Event-driven design for asynchronous operations
AR-004: CQRS pattern with separate models for update and display
Component Design:
CD-001: Modular design with clear interfaces and minimal dependencies
CD-002: Service components: Authentication, Recommendation, Image Processing, Planning
CD-003: Client components: Mobile App, Web App, Admin Console, API Gateway
CD-004: Integration components: Weather API, Market Data, Payment Gateway, SMS Gateway
User Interface Design:
VD-001: Consistent design system with outdoor-readable color palette
VD-002: Responsive design adapting to different screen sizes and orientations
VD-003: WCAG 2.1 Level AA compliance with high contrast and screen reader support
VD-004: Right-to-left text support, culturally appropriate imagery
Database Design:
DM-001: Core entities: User, Farm, Field, Crop, Activity, Record
DM-002: Relationship design with referential integrity and audit trails
DM-003: Multi-model database: PostgreSQL, MongoDB, Redis, Elasticsearch
DM-004: Performance optimization with indexing, partitioning, caching
Technology Stack:
TS-001: Frontend: Flutter, React.js, Redux/MobX, GraphQL
TS-002: Backend: Node.js/Express, Python, Java/Kotlin, Swift, Docker
TS-003: AI/ML: TensorFlow/PyTorch, Google Gemini AI, OpenCV, Scikit-learn
TS-004: Development: Git, CI/CD, Automated testing, Monitoring tools
3.6 System Model
3.6.1 Scenario
Title: Comprehensive Farm Management for Smallholder Farmer Tesfaye
Actors: Tesfaye (farmer), Worku (extension officer), Dr. Alem (expert), System AI
Setting: Oromia region, 2 hectares, mixed crops (teff, maize, vegetables)
Phase 1: Season Planning (January)
●	Tesfaye registers, maps fields, records soil types
●	System analyzes location (2400m elevation, 900mm rainfall)
●	Recommends improved teff variety based on soil and market analysis
●	Generates week-by-week plan with input requirements
Phase 2: Growing Season (February-May)
●	Weekly task reminders (land prep, planting, weeding)
●	Weather alerts for unexpected rain, irrigation adjustments
●	Image-based disease detection for maize rust
●	Treatment recommendations with organic options prioritized
Phase 3: Harvest and Marketing (June-July)
●	Yield prediction: 1.8 tons teff with 85% confidence
●	Market analysis: Prices rising in nearby markets
●	Recommends staggered selling for better prices
●	Connects with buyer through platform
Phase 4: Post-Season (August-December)
●	Performance analysis: 25% yield increase, 30% higher prices
●	Soil management recommendations for next season
●	Knowledge sharing in community forum
●	Planning for next season with lessons learned
